TreeSet in Java
`TreeSet` is a class in `java.util` that implements NavigableSet, SortedSet, Set, Collection, and Iterable.
It is a Red-Black Tree based implementation of the Set interface, meaning elements are stored in sorted order.
Key Characteristics
●	No duplicates allowed.
●	Sorted order maintained (natural ordering or via a custom Comparator).
●	Does not allow null elements (unlike HashSet or LinkedHashSet).
●	Provides logarithmic time complexity for add, remove, and search operations.
●	Useful when you need a sorted set with fast access.
Categorized Methods
1. Adding Elements
●	`add(E e)` – Adds element if not already present.
●	`addAll(Collection c)` – Adds all elements from another collection.
2. Removing Elements
●	`remove(Object o)` – Removes specified element if present.
●	`removeAll(Collection c)` – Removes all elements in given collection.
●	`clear()` – Removes all elements.
●	`retainAll(Collection c)` – Retains only elements present in given collection.
3. Searching & Checking
●	`contains(Object o)` – Checks if element exists.
●	`isEmpty()` – Checks if empty.
●	`size()` – Returns number of elements.
●	`equals(Object o)` – Compares with another set.
●	`hashCode()` – Returns hash code.
4. SortedSet Methods
●	`first()` – Returns first (lowest) element.
●	`last()` – Returns last (highest) element.
●	`headSet(E toElement)` – Returns elements less than toElement.
●	`tailSet(E fromElement)` – Returns elements greater than or equal to fromElement.
●	`subSet(E fromElement, E toElement)` – Returns elements between range.
5. NavigableSet Methods
●	`ceiling(E e)` – Returns least element ≥ e.
●	`floor(E e)` – Returns greatest element ≤ e.
●	`higher(E e)` – Returns least element > e.
●	`lower(E e)` – Returns greatest element < e.
●	`pollFirst()` – Retrieves and removes first element.
●	`pollLast()` – Retrieves and removes last element.
●	`descendingSet()` – Returns reverse order view.
6. Iteration Methods
●	`iterator()` – Returns iterator (ascending order).
●	`descendingIterator()` – Returns iterator (descending order).
●	`forEach(Consumer action)` – Performs action for each element.
●	`spliterator()` – Returns spliterator.
7. Conversion Methods
●	`toArray()` – Converts to array.
●	`toArray(T[] a)` – Converts to typed array.
Java Code Demonstration

import java.util.*;

public class TreeSetDemo {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        TreeSet<Integer> set = new TreeSet<>();

        // 1. Adding Elements
        set.add(10);
        set.add(5);
        set.add(20);
        set.addAll(Arrays.asList(15, 25, 30));

        // 2. Iteration (sorted order)
        for (Integer i : set) {
            System.out.println(i);
        }

        // 3. Removing Elements
        set.remove(20);
        set.removeAll(Arrays.asList(25, 30));
        set.retainAll(Arrays.asList(5, 10, 15));
        set.addAll(Arrays.asList(40, 50));
        System.out.println("After modifications: " + set);

        // 4. Searching & Checking
        System.out.println(set.contains(10));
        System.out.println(set.isEmpty());
        System.out.println(set.size());
        System.out.println(set.equals(new TreeSet<>(Arrays.asList(5, 10, 15, 40, 50))));
        System.out.println(set.hashCode());

        // 5. SortedSet Methods
        System.out.println("First: " + set.first());
        System.out.println("Last: " + set.last());
        System.out.println("HeadSet(15): " + set.headSet(15));
        System.out.println("TailSet(15): " + set.tailSet(15));
        System.out.println("SubSet(10, 40): " + set.subSet(10, 40));

        // 6. NavigableSet Methods
        System.out.println("Ceiling(12): " + set.ceiling(12));
        System.out.println("Floor(12): " + set.floor(12));
        System.out.println("Higher(15): " + set.higher(15));
        System.out.println("Lower(15): " + set.lower(15));
        System.out.println("PollFirst: " + set.pollFirst());
        System.out.println("PollLast: " + set.pollLast());
        System.out.println("DescendingSet: " + set.descendingSet());

        // 7. Iteration
        Iterator<Integer> it = set.iterator();
        while (it.hasNext()) System.out.println(it.next());

        Iterator<Integer> descIt = set.descendingIterator();
        while (descIt.hasNext()) System.out.println(descIt.next());

        set.forEach(System.out::println);
        Spliterator<Integer> spl = set.spliterator();
        spl.forEachRemaining(System.out::println);

        // 8. Conversion
        Object[] arr = set.toArray();
        Integer[] intArr = set.toArray(new Integer[0]);

        System.out.println("Array: " + Arrays.toString(intArr));
    }
}

